    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Nylandia spinosa</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_9648",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Stiff, rounded shrub growing to at least 1 m and with short spike-like lateral branches. Leaves small, stalkless, thick and oblong. Bears numerous small, solitary flowers that can be purplish or pink and white. The flowers are somewhat pea-like with the inner two sepals enlarged and petal-like and much longer than the others and a fringed crest on the lower, keeled petal. Fruit are conspicuous yellow-to-red fleshy globes.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9649",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Plants up to 1 m tall, flowers about 10 mm across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9650",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namaqualand to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9651",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common in coastal sands, but also widespread inland and come sometimes be the dominant species in the landscape. The fruits are astringent but are rich in Vitamin C and were eaten by early inhabitants of the Cape and are favoured by ostriches and other wildlife, including tortoises, hence the common name.</p><p>Popular in coastal gardens due to its profuse purple flowers and pretty berries, which also attract birds. The leaves and stems have been used to brew a tea that is believed to help with abdominal and digestive issues and the roots are also used in traditional medicine to treat malaria.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9652",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9653",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers from June to August.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9654",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This are numerous gorse-like regional species in this genus, but many of these have dry rather then fleshy fruits rather than fleshy berries. Can be confused with <i>M. scoparia,</i> which also has red thinly-fleshy fruits, but that species grows to 2.5 m, has longer, willowy branches and is confined to the West Coast.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9655",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
